                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-355-off1930 t18250915-355-victim1799"></join>
                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>JOHN RIDER. I am a <rs id="t18250915-355-viclabel1932" type="occupation">basket-maker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-355-victim1799 t18250915-355-viclabel1932"></join>. On the 27th of July, between nine and ten o'clock in the morning, I sent Jonathan Primatt to Bethlem Hospital, with three clothes baskets.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-355-person1800">
                  JONATHAN 
                  PRIMATT
               <interp inst="t18250915-355-person1800" type="surname" value="PRIMATT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-355-person1800" type="given" value="JONATHAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-355-person1800" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was eleven years of age last March. I am in Rider's employ. I was sent by him on the 27th of July, from Crispin-street, Spital-fields, to take three baskets to Bethlem Hospital; when I was near <placeName id="t18250915-355-crimeloc1933">London-bridge</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-355-crimeloc1933" type="placeName" value="London-bridge"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-355-crimeloc1933" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-355-off1930 t18250915-355-crimeloc1933"></join> I saw the prisoner Richardson, who asked me to go on an errand for him, and he would give me 2 d. - I said Yes; Adey was on the other side of the road, and Richardson gave him a penny to mind the baskets; I went on the errand, to carry a note to a gentleman - the gentleman said "It is not mine." I went back in about five minutes and the baskets were gone - I looked about and saw the officer with two men.</p>
               <p>Prisoner RICHARDSON. I saw the witness, and asked him to go for a pennyworth of biscuits, and he picked up the note and took it to the house. Witness. No; he gave me the note.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-355-person1801">
                  DANIEL 
                  FORRESTER
               <interp inst="t18250915-355-person1801" type="surname" value="FORRESTER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-355-person1801" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-355-person1801" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 27th of July I saw the prisoners together in Cheapside; I saw Richardson go to a lad who had a bag on his head, and speak to him for some time; I then followed the prisoners toward London-bridge, and when they got near to Eastcheap, Adey sat down on the end of the curb - Richardson went up to the witness who put the baskets down; in a few minutes Adey took them up - he and Richardson went away together - Adey pitched them down in George-street, and I took them into custody. I came back the same way, and found the witness, who was crying - he had two halfpence and this note in his hand.</p>
               <p>ADEY'S Defence. I never saw this prisoner before, but he asked me to carry the baskets for him.</p>
               <p>ADEY - <rs id="t18250915-355-verdict1934" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18250915-355-verdict1934" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 20.</p>
               <p>RICHARDSON - <rs id="t18250915-355-verdict1935" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18250915-355-verdict1935" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 12.</p>
